          "body": "The theological core of Ezekiel 9:4 is that the sole criterion for the protective mark is moral and emotional: sighing and groaning over the abominations of Jerusalem. The Hebrew *tav* — the final letter of the alphabet — was written in ancient script as a cross or X, which has generated significant typological discussion from Origen onward (Origen, *Selecta in Ezechielem*). But the mark's content matters more than its shape: it is placed on those whose hearts have not become numb to idolatry, whose grief over covenant betrayal is visceral enough to produce audible lamentation. This is not a mark of perfect obedience — the marked ones are not said to have avoided all participation in the city's sin. They are marked because they have not made peace with it. The pastoral implication is severe: complicity through silence, indifference to the abominations of one's own cultural moment, is not a neutral posture. In Ezekiel's vision, it is the posture of the unmarked."
